A quick intermediary step to makes ure the upscaler model didn't ruin the image!
Note that your browser is displaying a rescaled image, if you want better results use faststone image viewer, it's freeware and pixel-accurate.
Color matching can sometimes yield slight better results
This is your "prompt" - try changing the image by upping the CFG! ALWAYS test your prompts and models separately!
You can now add LORAs! Experiment with add_detail for example, or better faces perhaps!
a man dressed in an amusing outfit, highly detailed, 4k

Author: Stephan Tual
Date Updated: 03/28/2024
Version: 1.6.1 FLOWT.AI PUBLIC RELEASE _ Update 2

** HISTORY **
03/14/2024 - Releasing the workflow while recording the tutorial video
03/19/2024 - Updated post YouTube Video
03/28/2024 - Updated to support the recent update
03/29/2024 - Deployed on Flowt.AI Plug&Play and updated to support the 'red car' example
04/05/2024 - Added WDtagger so no one forgets their pos prompts. Please read the notes and watch the video on 'settings'
04/13/2024 - Updated for new video - check out my YT channel :)


** NOW RUNNING ON CLOUD!!! **
Thank you to flowt.ai for supporting this updated version at:
https://flowt.ai/community/supir-v2-plugandplay-edition-n5acf-v
The cloud is a good option if you lack vRAM, flowt has a 'plug and play' system that makes it really easy!


** PURPOSE **
A basic SUPIR worfklow supporting the latest update to keep up with the Jones.
Join our discord at tinyurl.com/URSIUM for showing of your work or sharing improved version of this workflow.


** SUPPORT **
If you experience an issue, first:
a) Rewatch the latest video: I cover most of the error messages
b) Run quick google search on the error message itself, works 99% of the time
c) Check the SUPIR nodes Github and post an issue.
Remember: I am not the author of the nodes. In addition, even they are rarely the authors of the underlying algorythms: most nodes are 'wrapping' code that may have bugs which neither myself nor the node authors can help with. You need to contact the correct person.
d) If all fails consider running this on the cloud, I test it regularly to make sure it's stable (see above links)


** DISCLAIMER **
This worfklow is provided 'AS IS' and is not supported in ANY way by the author. I am not responsible if the installation of custom nodes breaks your comfyUI install, or for anything for that matter. Each node used here is the property of their respective author - and they may contain non-commercial clauses. 


** USAGE ** 
0. Watch the tuturial video(s) posted on my YT channel (https://www.youtube.com/@stephantual)
1. Choose a photo - refer to the video for advice on settings for now please :)
2. Select an appropriate checkpoint for the model - anime for anime, photorealistic for photos etc.
3. Select a scale factor - the higher, the more vRam this will use
4. Run the stage 1 to check if you are happy with the model upscale - change the upscale model accordingly
5. Once happy, set the SUPIR sampler settings to default and run
6. Iterate until you have the results you want (creative, strict, etc)
7. Experiment! this is to learn, not an "app" :)


Discuss at tinyurl.com/URSIUM or for the Flowt version, tinyurl.com/flowtai
Run at: https://flowt.ai/community?search=%3Apub+Stephan_Tual
Remember: this lanczos image resize node are VERY RAM (not vRAM) hungry.
depending on your browser smoothing algorythm, if you're not using a model, you will NOT (AT ALL) see results from lanczos only here, this is normal. Use icat or faststone to compare images

The v2 nodes allow you to save a lot of time by upscaling/denoising the image first THEN passing it to supir with modified parameters! It's a useful way to iterate on SUPIR settings (only disable stage 2 to run stage 1, it doesn't work the other way around, evidently)

Match the steps and CFG to what is expected of your checkpoint like any other sampler.

for the 'red car' example, use a higher cfg than normal

for any other image, remember you have to change the settings per image. There is no 'one size fits all'

Use -1 to disable restoration. Max is 20. 

DMPPP_ETA and s (sigma) noise help create variations at low controlnet values, and/or can be used to simulate focus depth (see https://sandner.art/sigma-and-eta-noise-image-variations-in-latent-space-and-fast-detail-effects/)

Anything below 0.5 for cfg will start showing more of the underlying model. Fun for creative work, but can look strage.

Keep the model in memory if you are batching many images

Used the tiled sampler and set the tite size to the highest your vRam will allow, and reduce it according if you are low vRAM (8gb or less)

for higher denoise just leave the CN very low (at 0.1 it hallucinates)
